We are given a buggy Java function that computes a weighted variance. The code appears to be from Apache Commons Math. The bug is likely related to the calculation of sumWts: it sums over all weights (from 0 to weights.length) instead of only over the specified range (begin to begin+length). This would cause incorrect results when the function is called with a subrange. Also, the test function likely checks weights and values for non-negative etc., but the sumWts should be computed only for the range used.

The fix: change the loop for sumWts to iterate over i from begin to begin+length, using the same range as the values. Also note that the accum and accum2 are correctly computed over the range. So we need to compute sumWts only over that range.

The corrected code:

public double evaluate(final double[] values, final double[] weights,
                       final double mean, final int begin, final int length) {

    double var = Double.NaN;

    if (test(values, weights, begin, length)) {
        if (length == 1) {
            var = 0.0;
        } else if (length > 1) {
            double accum = 0.0;
            double dev = 0.0;
            double accum2 = 0.0;
            for (int i = begin; i < begin + length; i++) {
                dev = values[i] - mean;
                accum += weights[i] * (dev * dev);
                accum2 += weights[i] * dev;
            }

            double sumWts = 0;
            for (int i = begin; i < begin + length; i++) {
                sumWts += weights[i];
            }

            if (isBiasCorrected) {
                var = (accum - (accum2 * accum2 / sumWts)) / (sumWts - 1.0);
            } else {
                var = (accum - (accum2 * accum2 / sumWts)) / sumWts;
            }
        }
    }
    return var;
}

